The '''Captive bubble method''' is a method for measuring [[contact angle]] between a liquid and a solid, by using drop shape analysis.<ref>[http://www.ramehart.com/glossary.htm#captive_bubble ramé-hart instrument co.]</ref> In this method, a [[:wikt:bubble|bubble]] of [[air]] is injected beneath a solid, the surface of which is located in the [[liquid]], instead of placing a [[drop (liquid)|drop]] on the [[solid]] as in the case of the [[sessile drop technique]].
The method is particularly suitable for solids with high [[surface free energy]] on which liquids spread out. [[Hydrogel]]s, such as soft [[contact lens]]es for example, are likewise inaccessible for the standard arrangement; the captive bubble method is also used in such cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.biolinscientific.com/zafepress.php?url=%2Fpdf%2FAttension%2FApplication%20Notes%2FAT_AN_8_captive-bubble.pdf# |title=Captive bubble method in Contact lens |access-date=2015-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207172534/http://www.biolinscientific.com/zafepress.php?url=%2Fpdf%2FAttension%2FApplication%20Notes%2FAT_AN_8_captive-bubble.pdf# |archive-date=2015-02-07 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
