[[File:PZSL1907Plate47.png|thumb|Woodward's illustrations of two catfish species, 1908]]
'''Gertrude Mary Woodward''' (1854–1939) was a British [[Biological illustration|scientific illustrator]]. The daughter of geologist [[Henry Bolingbroke Woodward]] and sister of illustrator [[Alice Woodward]], she illustrated many [[palaeontological]] works for the [[Natural History Museum, London]] and  was esteemed by her peers for her the accuracy and quality of her [[watercolour]] work. She illustrated the famous [[Piltdown man]] fossils and other works by [[Arthur Smith Woodward]] (unrelated), as well as works by zoologist [[Ray Lankester]].<ref name=ForgottenWomen>{{cite book|last1=Turner|first1=S.|last2=Burek|first2=C. V.|last3=Moody|first3=R. T. J.|chapter=Forgotten women in an extinct saurian (man's) world|date=2010|volume=343|pages=111–153|title=Dinosaurs and Other Extinct Saurians: A Historical Perspective|editor=Moody, Richard|series=Geological Society, London, Special Publications|doi=10.1144/SP343.7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ym2ei7Ey0PwC&pg=PA135|isbn=9781862393110}}</ref><ref name="JohansonBarrett2016">{{cite book|author1=Z. Johanson|author2=P.M. Barrett|author3=M. Richter|author4=M. Smith|title=Arthur Smith Woodward: His Life and Influence on Modern Vertebrate Palaeontology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4EafCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA78|date=2016|publisher=Geological Society of London|isbn=978-1-86239-741-5|page=78}}</ref>

