'''Organa''' is the informal name given to a [[Impact crater|crater]] on [[Pluto]]'s largest [[moon]], [[Charon (moon)|Charon]]. The crater was discovered by [[NASA]]'s ''[[New Horizons]]'' [[space probe]] on its flyby of Pluto. The name was chosen as a reference to [[Leia Organa]] from the ''[[Star Wars]]'' media franchise in the theme of naming Charon's craters after science fiction characters. Organa crater is rich in frozen ammonia, which suggests it was created very recently.<ref name="ammonia">{{cite web|last1=Talbert|first1=Tricia|title=The Youngest CraterThe Youngest Crater on Charon?|url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/the-youngest-crater-on-charon|website=NASA|publisher=National Aeronautics and Space Administration|accessdate=16 April 2018|language=en|date=29 October 2015}}</ref> The location of Organa crater is in the northern Pluto-facing hemisphere of Charon.
==Ammonia== [[file:Organa crater.jpg|thumb|300px|A composite image showing the ammonia around Organa crater, in green.]] Organa crater is the only known crater on Charon that contains abundant [[ammonia]]. The ammonia was detected using the ''New Horizons'' LEISA instrument, by observing an absorption of [[infrared]] light in the {{val|2.22|u=[[Micrometre|μm]]}} band, which is associated with ammonia.<ref name="Stern"/>
The source of the ammonia has not been confirmed, but it is associated with the impact process that created Organa crater, perhaps by removing the overlaying layer of water of ice and [[regolith]].<ref name="Ames">{{cite journal|last1=Cruikshank|first1=D. P.|title=Pluto and Charon: Surface Colors and Compositions - A Hypothesis|journal=47th Lunar and Planetary Science Conference|date=Mar 21, 2016|url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp?R=20160003677|accessdate=24 April 2018}}</ref> If this is confirmed, the detection could indicate that Charon has experienced [[Cryovolcano|cyrovolcanic]] activity, with ammonia as magma.<ref name="Owlcation">{{cite web|last1=Kelley|first1=Leonard|title=The Secrets of Pluto's Moons, Including Charon, Styx, Hydra, Kerberos, and Nix|url=https://owlcation.com/stem/The-Secrets-of-Plutos-Moons-Including-Charon-Styx-Hydra-Kerberos-and-Nix|website=Owlcation|publisher=[[HubPages Inc.]]|accessdate=24 April 2018|language=en}}</ref> This interpretation is puzzling, since cryovolcanism isn't known to occur on such small bodies.<ref name="Stern"/> In this scenario, the ammonia may have [[Precipitation|precipitated]] from an atmosphere, or soaked the ground from a subsurface source, or diffused out of the existing [[tholin]].<ref name="Owlcation"/>
An alternate explanation suggests the deposit of ammonia was delivered by the impactor that created Organa crater.<ref name="ammonia"/> In either case, it is believed that Organa crater is the result of a recent impact, less than 10 million years ago.<ref name="Stern">{{Cite arxiv |last1=Stern |first1=S. Alan |last2=Grundy |first2=William |last3=McKinnon |first3=William B |last4=Weaver |first4=Harold A |last5=Young |first5=Leslie A |year=2017 |title=The Pluto System After New Horizons |eprint=1712.<!--So Citation Bot stops converting to cite journal-->05669 |class=astro-ph.EP}}</ref> The impact that created Organa crater may have been so recent that the ammonia hasn't yet been destroyed by [[radiation]] from space.<ref name="wired">{{cite web|last1=Stockton|first1=Nick|title=Charon's Organa Crater Glows With the Force ... Er, Ammonia|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/10/charons-organa-crater-glows-with-the-force-er-ammonia/|website=WIRED|publisher=Condé Nast Publications|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>
